<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="123" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="24.[136,1452,266,1696]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,493,1273,1300]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
—This species is found in Central and South America, from 
<collectingCountry box="[1191,1280,1274,1300]" name="Panama" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Panama</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1320,1402,1274,1300]" name="Bolivia" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
and Central 
<collectingCountry box="[227,295,1310,1336]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J." box="[311,635,1310,1336]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" pagination="928 - 941" refId="ref27951" refString="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J. (1991) A Revision of Raddiella (Poaceae: Bambusoideae: Olyreae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 78 (4): 928 - 941." type="journal article" year="1991">Zuloaga &amp; Judziewicz 1991</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[687,758,1310,1336]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is registered in the North (AM, AP, PA, RO, RR and 
<collectingRegion box="[1398,1439,1310,1336]" country="Brazil" name="TO" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">TO</collectingRegion>
), Northeast (BA, MA and 
<collectingRegion box="[419,447,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="PI" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">PI</collectingRegion>
), Central-West (DF, GO, MT and 
<collectingRegion box="[839,883,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="MS" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">MS</collectingRegion>
), Southeast (MG and 
<collectingRegion box="[1135,1167,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="SP" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">SP</collectingRegion>
) and South (
<collectingRegion box="[1315,1352,1346,1372]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">PR</collectingRegion>
) regions (Oliveira &amp; Oliveira 2020). It can be found in gallery forests and savannas, in semi-shaded or dryish open areas, up to 1.500 meters (
<bibRefCitation author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J." box="[331,658,1418,1444]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" pagination="928 - 941" refId="ref27951" refString="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J. (1991) A Revision of Raddiella (Poaceae: Bambusoideae: Olyreae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 78 (4): 928 - 941." type="journal article" year="1991">Zuloaga &amp; Judziewicz 1991</bibRefCitation>
). In the Serra do Cachimbo, it was found in 
<emphasis box="[1175,1355,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Campo cerrado</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Campo" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestre">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Campo rupestre</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Open ombrophilous forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[136,1452,266,1696]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,328,1489,1515]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Comments:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. E. Calderon &amp; Soderstrom" authorityYear="1980" baseAuthorityName="Steudel" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[356,589,1490,1516]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Raddiella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">
<emphasis box="[356,589,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">Raddiella esenbeckii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Judziewicz &amp; Zuloaga" authorityName="Judziewicz &amp; Zuloaga" box="[645,1022,1490,1516]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Raddiella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis box="[645,760,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">R. minima</emphasis>
Judziewicz &amp; Zuloaga
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<bibRefCitation author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J." box="[1068,1444,1490,1516]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" pagination="928 - 941" refId="ref27951" refString="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J. (1991) A Revision of Raddiella (Poaceae: Bambusoideae: Olyreae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 78 (4): 928 - 941." type="journal article" year="1991">Zuloaga &amp; Judziewicz 1991: 939</bibRefCitation>
) share asymmetrical ovate-triangular leaves, that are truncate at the base and female spikelets with persistent glumes. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. E. Calderon &amp; Soderstrom" authorityYear="1980" baseAuthorityName="Steudel" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[251,399,1562,1588]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Raddiella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">
<emphasis box="[251,399,1562,1588]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">R. esenbeckii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized by the culms 
<quantity box="[782,879,1562,1588]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" unit="cm" value="24.0" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="8.0">8–40 cm</quantity>
tall (vs. 
<quantity box="[976,1059,1562,1588]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3–6 cm</quantity>
long in 
<taxonomicName box="[1151,1266,1563,1588]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Raddiella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis box="[1151,1266,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="123">R. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), blades 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" unit="cm" value="1.65" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.8 cm</quantity>
long (vs. 
<quantity box="[290,417,1598,1624]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" unit="cm" value="0.5" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.4">0.4–0.6 cm</quantity>
long) and the axillary synflorescences bearing male and female spikelets (vs. the axillary synflorescences bearing only female spikelets). It also can be distinguished by the long-ellipsoid caryopsis, with the hilum short-linear, ca. 1/3 the length the caryopsis (
<bibRefCitation author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J." box="[712,1032,1670,1696]" pageId="24" pageNumber="123" pagination="928 - 941" refId="ref27951" refString="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Judziewicz, E. J. (1991) A Revision of Raddiella (Poaceae: Bambusoideae: Olyreae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 78 (4): 928 - 941." type="journal article" year="1991">Zuloaga &amp; Judziewicz 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
